on a three-year project concentrating on the design and implementation of a coordinated program for the treatment of child sexual abuse in rural Manitoba. The project was unusual in that it followed a rigorous research design which incorporated a matched comparison of test and control communities and assessed the impact of a ‘coordinated service model’ at family, agency, and community levels. It was also one of the rare studies to date that offered detailed information on service delivery in rural communities and assessed the impact of a ‘coordinated service model’ at family, agency, and community levels. It was also one of the rare studies to date that offered detailed information on service delivery in rural communities, including rich case material to highlight salient practice themes at both case and community levels. The book is divided into three sections: design and implementation of coordinated community services, evaluation of coordinated services, and reflections on community experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamily counselingzCanada. 0aFamily counselingzManitoba. 0aIncest victimsxServices forzCanada. 0aIncest victimsxServices forzManitoba. 0aRural childrenxServices forzCanada. 0aRural childrenxServices forzManitoba. 0aSexually abused childrenxServices forzCanada. 0aSexually abused childrenxServices forzManitoba. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAdkins, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDonald, George , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMacDonald, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTrute, Barry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTrute, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle i